      {
        "id": 2895802,
        "name": "William Kelley",
        "username": "William_Kelley",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/william_kelley/{size}/2314_2.png",
        "created_at": "2020-05-21T15:48:22.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-post=\"1\" data-topic=\"161199\">\n<blockquote>\n<p>On the nose reduction is immediately evident, say gunpowder and even some cornflakes (there is a different thread in which the someone mentions this characteristic on white burgundy, but I forgot where).</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Honestly, I think the aromatic signatures to which you are referring are more to do with cooperage choices (Chassin, Gauthier and a few others IIRC) that reduction per se. I have never had a reduced 2014 Ramonet, personally. That said, I think I have a magnum of the Morgeots but no bottles, and it has been a few years since I tasted it at the domaine.</p>\n<p>While I agree that 2014s are a bit more incisive than 2013s, 2012s and 2011s chez Ramonet, I think that\u2019s just a vintage thing. I find them structured along quite similar lines to the 2010s, just a bit younger.</p>",
